          "title": "Attached pronouns: suffix straight onto the noun",
          "explanation": "Instead of 'dar tiegħi' (my house), Maltese often attaches a tiny suffix to the noun: dari. The suffixes are -i (my), -ek (your), -u (his), -ha (her), -na (our), -kom (your pl), -hom (their). The article drops away.",
          "letters": [
            "-i (my)",
            "-ek (your)",
            "-u (his)",
            "-ha (her)",
            "-na (our)",
            "-kom (your pl)",
            "-hom (their)"
          ],
          "examples": [
            {
              "mt": "dar tiegħi → dari",
              "en": "my house"
            },
            {
              "mt": "dar tiegħek → darek",
              "en": "your house"
            },
            {
              "mt": "dar tiegħu → daru",
              "en": "his house"
            },
            {
              "mt": "missier tagħha → missierha",
              "en": "her father"
            },
            {
              "mt": "missier tagħna → missierna",
              "en": "our father"
            },
            {
              "mt": "qalb tiegħi → qalbi",
              "en": "my heart"
            },
            {
              "mt": "art tagħhom → arthom",
              "en": "their land"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "family-plurals",
          "title": "Family member plurals are irregular",
          "explanation": "Family-member plurals don't follow a single pattern, many take -ijiet or -iet, some are completely different. Memorise the pairs.",
          "examples": [
